## SOP: Build and Configure an Active Directory Lab on Windows Server 2025 in Azure

### Objective

Create a fully functional Active Directory domain controller in Microsoft Azure, then configure core identity, organizational, policy, and help desk administration tasks. This SOP provides a repeatable workflow for setting up the lab, validating the environment, and performing common day-one IT support actions.

### Key Steps

**1. Prepare the Azure lab environment and connect to the server** [1:07](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=67)

![generated-image-at-00:01:07](https://loom.com/i/00575101a56f4058bad46253f287f607?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Sign in to Microsoft Azure and locate the virtual machine created for the lab.
- Download the RDP file for the VM and connect remotely.
- Confirm the VM is running before proceeding.
- Enable clipboard sharing in the RDP settings so commands can be copied from your local machine into the server.
- Verify you are connected to the Windows Server desktop and can access Server Manager.

**2. Confirm the server platform and required roles** [1:43](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=103)

![generated-image-at-00:01:43](https://loom.com/i/680778ab17e04d9fb67e8ae34f1fd33e?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Verify the server is running **Windows Server 2025 Datacenter** in Azure.
- Confirm the VM size is appropriate for the lab environment (the walkthrough uses a small B2 VM).
- Open **Server Manager** and confirm the required roles are present: 
  - Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS)
  - DNS
- Open PowerShell or PowerShell ISE to begin validation and administration tasks.
- Run a verification command such as `Get-ADDomainController` to confirm the server is functioning as a domain controller.

**3. Install AD DS and promote the server to a domain controller** [3:26](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=206)

![generated-image-at-00:03:26](https://loom.com/i/2ac033f83d3242fdbd579a0882584ff9?workflows_screenshot=true)

- In **Server Manager**, go to **Manage &gt; Add Roles and Features**.
- Select and install the **Active Directory Domain Services** role.
- Install supporting management tools and any required policy components.
- Promote the server to a domain controller.
- Create the domain **lab.local** during promotion.
- Confirm the server is now the authoritative domain controller and DNS source for the domain.

**4. Create the Active Directory organizational structure** [4:36](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=276)

![generated-image-at-00:04:36](https://loom.com/i/88d40baf147547c0a34675a9d1b5d5f3?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Open **Active Directory Users and Computers**.
- Create the following Organizational Units (OUs): 
  - IT
  - Finance
  - HR
  - Sales
  - Computers
- Use OUs to separate users and devices by department.
- Treat OUs as the structure that Group Policy will target later.
- Keep computer accounts in a separate OU for easier management and policy application.

**5. Create department users and security groups** [5:45](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=345)

![generated-image-at-00:05:45](https://loom.com/i/3ccd76d38a904361ba0e91a3745eb7e8?workflows_screenshot=true)

- For each department, create a security group to control access.
- Create one user account per department for the lab: 
  - Alice.Chen — IT
  - Bob.Patel — Finance
  - Carol.Jones — HR
  - David.Smith — Sales
- Add each user to the correct department security group.
- Use group membership instead of assigning permissions directly to users.
- Verify that access is controlled through role-based access control (RBAC) via group membership.

**6. Verify group membership with PowerShell** [6:30](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=390)

![generated-image-at-00:06:30](https://loom.com/i/d266c5f02fe94390b7e47e4c58c89274?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Open PowerShell and run a group membership verification command.
- Confirm that each user is assigned to the correct department group.
- Use this step to validate that access will be inherited correctly from the group.
- Remember the operating principle: 
  - Assign permissions to groups
  - Add or remove users from groups as needed
- Use this method to scale access management efficiently across many users.

**7. Create and link the IT security Group Policy Object** [7:39](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=459)

![generated-image-at-00:07:39](https://loom.com/i/f0760da240914620a4a787ece5c7f439?workflows_screenshot=true)

- In **Server Manager**, go to **Tools &gt; Group Policy Management**.
- Right-click the **IT** OU and create a new GPO linked to that OU.
- Name the GPO **IT Security Policy**.
- Confirm the link prompt and save the new policy.
- Open the GPO for editing so you can configure security settings.

**8. Configure password and logon security settings** [8:20](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=500)

![generated-image-at-00:08:20](https://loom.com/i/51910c1e1b944fe991d3116a01616a31?workflows_screenshot=true)

- In the GPO editor, navigate to the security policy settings.
- Set **Minimum password length** to **12 characters**.
- Enable **Password must meet complexity requirements**.
- Configure interactive logon settings under computer configuration.
- Set the interactive logon limit to **900 seconds**.
- Apply and save the policy changes.

**9. Restrict removable storage access** [10:00](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=600)

![generated-image-at-00:10:00](https://loom.com/i/a9ecad041fb74d50b9fb8386f0d6b6da?workflows_screenshot=true)

- In the same GPO, navigate to the removable storage policy area.
- Locate the setting for **All Removable Storage classes**.
- Set the policy to **Deny all access**.
- Enable the policy and save the configuration.
- Use this control to reduce data leakage and unauthorized device use.

**10. Perform a password reset for a user account** [10:56](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=656)

![generated-image-at-00:10:56](https://loom.com/i/82c29eca7e694f2f898f0534c5172196?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Open PowerShell to perform a help desk-style password reset.
- Reset **Bob.Patel**’s password using the appropriate account command.
- Set the account so the user must change the password at next logon.
- Use a secure string when entering the new password.
- Confirm the command runs without errors before moving on.

**11. Unlock a locked account** [15:17](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=917)

![generated-image-at-00:15:17](https://loom.com/i/cf4c981034db487a8b313ac3b41f0a33?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Identify the locked user account that needs to be restored.
- Use PowerShell to unlock **Carol.Jones**’s account.
- Confirm the command completes successfully with no errors.
- Verify the account is available for the user to log in again.
- Use this process when a user is locked out after failed sign-in attempts.

**12. Disable a departing employee account** [16:23](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=983)

![generated-image-at-00:16:23](https://loom.com/i/e64ab89d426544e897d52c2b9d2512a7?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Identify the user account for the departing employee.
- Disable **David.Smith**’s account instead of deleting it.
- Preserve the account for audit history, group membership, and compliance needs.
- Understand that disabling is reversible, while deletion is permanent.
- Use this approach when an employee leaves the organization.

**13. Audit account status and confirm changes** [17:21](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=1041)

![generated-image-at-00:17:21](https://loom.com/i/3519bb8b44e14823a3577a50bad83e24?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Run a search or query to list account status changes.
- Confirm which accounts were unlocked, disabled, or otherwise modified.
- Use the output to report status to a manager or security team.
- Verify that the changes match the intended administrative actions.
- Keep this step as part of routine administrative auditing.

**14. Review the automation script and documentation** [18:25](https://loom.com/share/6e8394eb254a4af2bf66ff90e17feb81?t=1105)

![generated-image-at-00:18:25](https://loom.com/i/71e028225b7f4baaa13358aa8190fd03?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Open the lab automation script in the GitHub repository.
- Review the script sections that match each lab task.
- Use the region markers to run individual blocks as needed.
- Read the inline comments to understand both the command and the business reason behind it.
- Use the README and screenshots to verify each step and map the lab to real job tasks.

### Cautionary Notes

- Do not delete user accounts when a simple disable action is sufficient; deletion removes audit history and can create compliance issues.
- Always verify PowerShell syntax before running commands; incorrect syntax will generate errors and may prevent changes from applying.
- Be careful when editing Group Policy Objects, since linked policies can affect all users and computers in the targeted OU.
- Use clipboard sharing in RDP only in a controlled lab or approved environment.
- Ensure you are working in the correct OU and on the correct user account before making changes.

### Tips for Efficiency

- Use PowerShell ISE or another editor to reduce typing errors and make commands easier to review.
- Keep the lab script in a repository so each task can be rerun quickly and consistently.
- Organize users, groups, and computers by OU from the start to make Group Policy easier to manage.
- Prefer group-based permissions over direct user permissions to simplify administration at scale.
- Use verification commands after each major change to confirm success before moving to the next step.
- Document each change with comments or screenshots so the lab can be repeated or audited later.

